<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-466-440  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 466 440.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computing Canada  June 22 1989 v15 n13 pS35(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Good as new; used equipment has a bright future. (Report on DECspecial supplement)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Pollack, Sheldon.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Sales for re-marketers of used DEC hardware are forecast toincrease significantly.andP;  Whenever a particular product is heavilydiscounted, used equipment prices are forced down.andP;  A company thatplans to increase its computing power by purchasing used anddiscounted equipment thus decreases the worth of its existingequipment, which it wishes to replace.andP;  So however much the usergains through the discount on the equipment being purchased, thesame amount is lost through the proportionate devaluation of theequipment being replaced.andP;  The companies that stand to lose themost from this situation are those that require new,state-of-the-art equipment, since companies that need only betterused equipment, and are attracted to the discounts, drive down theworth of all used equipment through their purchases.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Digital Equipment Corp. (marketing).andO;Ticker:    DEC.andO;Topic:     Used EquipmentProduct Life CycleDiscount HardwareComputer RetailingMarketingMarket Analysis.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>